iAt 1103.150 Kbit/s, it's three times faster than `/dev/random` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isignificantly boosting performance for random-number-dependent		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iapplications. However, most programs only recognize `/dev/random` and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iignore hardware RNGs. How to address this?		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs mentioned earlier, `/dev/random` is slow. To mitigate this, Linux		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iemploys a "randomness pool": when random numbers aren't needed, Linux		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
igradually collects entropy from system activities in the background		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand stores it in the `/dev/random` pool. During sudden high demand, it		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idraws from this pool to handle bursts without stuttering. Thus, we can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifeed random numbers from `/dev/hwrng` into the `/dev/random` pool. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inecessary tools are in the rng-tools package:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  sudo apt-get install rng-tools		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  sudo nano /etc/default/rng-tools		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # 添加以下内容		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  HRNGDEVICE=/dev/hwrng		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  RNGDOPTIONS="--fill-watermark=50% --feed-interval=1"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # 保存，最后运行以下命令		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  sudo service rng-tools restart		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe `HRNGDEVICE` line specifies the source of supplemental randomness —		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihere we point it to the hardware RNG. Some tutorials suggest setting		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithis to `/dev/urandom` , but as noted earlier, urandom isn't secure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ienough and would compromise system security.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn `RNGDOPTIONS` , `--fill-watermark` replenishes the pool to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ispecified capacity (here 50%) when entropy is low. We avoid 100%		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibecause hardware RNG implementations vary across vendors and are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itypically undisclosed, raising concerns about potential hidden		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibackdoors. Filling to 100% implies full trust in the hardware RNG,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhich could pose security risks.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`--feed-interval` sets the interval for slow replenishment after		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireaching the target capacity; `1` is generally sufficient.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter this configuration, `/dev/random` 's random number generation		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iefficiency will improve dramatically.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
